By contrast, Sounds of Summer: Very Best of The Beach Boys, while excellent in its own right, is less well matched to my priorities. Its strengths — dense, multi‑part vocal harmonies and inventive, layered studio arrangements — reward repeated, high‑fidelity listening to uncover production details, but those very characteristics can conflict with my dislikes: layered, studio‑heavy mixes and lavish production can reduce the intimacy and lyric clarity I prize and move focus away from a simple duo vocal center and acoustic immediacy. The Beach Boys compilation is career‑spanning and therefore spans many production styles and eras, which tends to reduce the single‑mood, album‑like cohesion I favor; its emphasis is on rich studio texture and complexity rather than the front‑and‑center, lyric‑forward duo intimacy that defines my preferred listening.
Given the strong overlap between my stated preference for duo harmony, clear lyric delivery, intimate/acoustic‑leaning arrangements, and well‑sequenced compilations — and the explicit attributes of the Simon & Garfunkel anthology — I select Best of Simon & Garfunkel and reject Sounds of Summer for not matching my core priorities around vocal intimacy, lyric clarity, and restrained, supportive production.

